  "doc_id": "15031",
  "text": "Almost hundreds of studies have been carried out on fuzzy PO in the past 30 years. One of the most important ones was the study carried out by [CITATION_1] . In that study, a dynamic PO model was developed by fuzzifying the uncertainty of the future prices and risks of the assets. Ramaswamy [CITATION_2] developed fuzzy multi-criteria linear programming models for several rates of return levels. Fuzziness was applied to the subjective decisions of investors for an uncertain period via trapezoidal membership function. The objective was the fuzzified utility maximization. Tanaka and Guo [CITATION_3] used possibility distributions instead of average variance for representing the knowledge of decision-makers. They partially rejected the assumption of Markowitz regarding the effectiveness of the past data in the future by integrating it with the knowledge and judgments of decision-makers. They generated an exponential possibility distribution for each decision-maker and integrated them into one. According to [CITATION_4] , PO models should have considered the nature of the data, risk and return expectations. In this regard, they examined several approaches regarding the data uncertainty and re-optimized the infeasible models by using duality theory and fuzzy programming. Another fuzzy PO model that was based on MVM was developed by Watada [CITATION_5] . The satisfaction level for the expected return and risk was defined by a logistic membership function.",
